Challenge #16

1. Install the tree command which is necessary.

2. Using shell commands create the following directory structure.

linux/
	centos/
		commands.txt
		security.txt
		updates/
			latest
	ubuntu/
		apt.txt


3. Considering this directory structure, copy the file called security.txt to the updates directory.

4. Considering the solution from the previous challenge remove the file called security.txt from the directory called updates.

5. Considering the initial directory structure, copy the directory called updates from centos to ubuntu.

6. Considering the solution from the previous challenge, remove the directory called updates from the ubuntu directory.

7. Considering the initial directory structure and using only one command copy the file called apt.txt and the directory called updates to linux directory.

8. Considering the solution from the previous challenge remove the file called apt.txt and the directory called updates from the linux directory interactively (by prompting the user).

9. Considering the initial directory structure, rename the directory called centos to redhat and then back to centos.

10. Considering the initial directory structure, copy the file called security.txt to ubuntu directory as sec.txt

    a) Create a file named users.txt by redirecting the output of the who command.

    b) Display the file contents.

    c) Remove the file in a secure manner by overwriting the file 50 times before removing it.

11. Remove the entire directory structure without prompting.
